Problem Statement¶

Lyra Health is looking to expand its products to include an online full service pharmacy, which delivers medication to their clients. One of the demographic groups that the company is interested in is the elderly population. Should Lyra Health target this group and what states should they look into?

Import Libraries¶

Importing and Cleaning Dataset¶

Medicare Part D Prescriber Public Use File¶

(Source: https://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/Medicare-Provider-Charge-Data/PartD2017.html)

This dataset provides information on prescription drugs prescribed by individual physicians and other health care providers and paid for under the Medicare Part D Prescription Drug Program. It contains the overall drug utilization (number of claims, number of 30-Day fills, and number of day’s supply), total drug costs, and beneficiary counts organized at the provider level.

In [27]:
def dist_graph(colname):
    f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1)
    sns.distplot(us_provider[colname], ax = ax1)
    us_provider.boxplot(colname, ax = ax2)
    plt.show()

metrics = ['total_claim_count', 'total_30_day_fill_count', 'total_drug_cost', 'total_day_supply']
for colname in metrics:
    dist_graph(colname)

Above is a statistical summary of the numerical variables. It summarizes the central tendency, dispersion and shape of a dataset’s distribution, excluding NaN values. As shown, there seems to be an extremely high variation for total_claim_count, total_30_day_fill_count, total_drug_cost, and total_day_supply. The distribution plots and box plots illustrates that the distribution is highly right skewed. The data is from CMS’s Chronic Conditions Data Warehouse, which contains Prescription Drug Event records submitted by Medicare Advantage Prescription Drug (MAPD) plans and by stand-alone Prescription Drug Plans (PDP). To determine the validity in the value of these outliers, I would need to research more on how the records were submitted. However, for this analysis, I will accept the values as is.

There are 18 columns that are missing values.

3 of the providers in the dataset are organizations; therefore, it makes sense that the 'nppes_provider_gender' is missing 3 values. These values will be filled in with "Other".

Most columns have null values because count values fewer than 11 are suppressed and are indicated by a blank for privacy purposes. (See https://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/Medicare-Provider-Charge-Data/Downloads/Prescriber_Methods.pdf)

Not treating these values will underestimate the true value; therefore, I will fill these suppressed values with 5.

In [76]:
# Fill in Gender
us_provider['nppes_provider_gender'] = us_provider['nppes_provider_gender'].fillna('Other')

# Fill in suppressed values
suppressed_cols = ['bene_count', 'beneficiary_age_less_65_count',
       'beneficiary_age_65_74_count', 'beneficiary_age_75_84_count',
       'beneficiary_age_greater_84_count', 'beneficiary_female_count',
       'beneficiary_male_count', 'beneficiary_race_white_count',
       'beneficiary_race_black_count', 'beneficiary_race_asian_pi_count',
       'beneficiary_race_hispanic_count', 'beneficiary_race_nat_ind_count',
       'beneficiary_race_other_count', 'beneficiary_nondual_count',
       'beneficiary_dual_count']

us_provider[suppressed_cols] = us_provider[suppressed_cols].fillna(5)
del(suppressed_cols)

The last 2 columns that need to be filled are average values. As illustrated by the boxplots below, the distributions tend to be skewed with outliers. I will fill the missing values with the median since it best represents the central value.

Aggregating Data by State¶

Categorical variables, such as provider gender, will be aggregated by the most common value in the column. In the case that there are multiple modes, any one of the modes will be picked as the mode.

Certain continuous variables need to be aggregated by a certain function. Variables representing the total must be aggregated using the sum function while the average variables must be aggregated by the mean function.

In [79]:
# Dataframe for continuous variables

# Dictionary of aggregate function for each continuous variable
dtypes = us_provider.dtypes
dtypes_col = dtypes.index
dtypes_type = [i.name for i in dtypes.values]
agg_types = dict(zip(dtypes_col, dtypes_type))
agg_types = {key:'sum' for key, value in agg_types.items() if value != 'object'}

agg_types['npi'] = 'count'
agg_types['average_age_of_beneficiaries'] = 'mean'
agg_types['beneficiary_average_risk_score'] = 'mean'

state_df = us_provider.groupby('nppes_provider_state', as_index = False).agg(agg_types).rename(columns = {'nppes_provider_state': 'state', 'npi': 'provider_count'})
state_df['nppes_provider_gender'] = us_provider.groupby(['nppes_provider_state'], as_index=False)['nppes_provider_gender'].agg(pd.Series.mode)['nppes_provider_gender']
state_df['specialty_description'] = us_provider.groupby(['nppes_provider_state'], as_index=False)['specialty_description'].agg(lambda x: pd.Series.mode(x)[0])['specialty_description']

Scaling Variables for State Comparison¶

In order to compare the demographic counts across states, the counts values must be converted into percentages in respect to the total beneficiaries across the respective subgroups. I will then classify each state by their most prominent category per subgroup.

In [80]:
dem_age = [s for s in state_df.columns if "beneficiary_age" in s]
dem_gen = ['beneficiary_female_count', 'beneficiary_male_count']
dem_race = [s for s in state_df.columns if "beneficiary_race" in s]
dem_dual = ['beneficiary_nondual_count', 'beneficiary_dual_count']

dem_total = [dem_age, dem_gen, dem_race, dem_dual]
for total in dem_total:
    total_ben = state_df[total].sum(axis=1)
    for column in total:
        colname = column.replace('count', 'pct')
        state_df[colname] = state_df[column]/total_ben
        
state_df['beneficiary_age'] = [x.replace('beneficiary_age_', '').replace('_count', '') for x in state_df[dem_age].idxmax(axis=1)]
state_df['beneficiary_gender'] = [x.replace('beneficiary_', '').replace('_count', '') for x in state_df[dem_gen].idxmax(axis=1)]
state_df['beneficiary_race'] = [x.replace('beneficiary_race_', '').replace('_count', '') for x in state_df[dem_race].idxmax(axis=1)]
state_df['beneficiary_dual'] = [x.replace('beneficiary_', '').replace('_count', '') for x in state_df[dem_dual].idxmax(axis=1)]

In order to compare total values across different states, the value must be on the same scale. These values will be divided by the total number of beneficiaries per state so that the values will be in terms of per beneficiary. I have chosen to put these columns in terms of per beneficiary rather than per provider since each prescription is written per beneficiary.

In [81]:
total_std = ['total_claim_count', 'total_30_day_fill_count', 'total_drug_cost', 'total_day_supply']

for column in total_std:
    colname = column + '_per_beneficiary'
    state_df[colname] = state_df[column]/state_df.bene_count

However, to compare the beneficiary count value, the variable must be in terms of per provider.

state_df['bene_count_per_provider'] = state_df.bene_count/state_df.provider_count

## DEMOGRAPHICS OF PROVIDERS
# Editing numbers
import locale
locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'en_US')

# Create Leaflet map
from folium.map import *

m = folium.Map([43, -100], zoom_start=4)

## Provider Count Layer
choropleth = folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=us_states,
    data= final_state,
    columns=['state', 'provider_count'],
    key_on='feature.id',
    fill_color='YlGn',
    name='Provider Distribution',
    legend_name='Provider Count (#)'
).add_to(m)

# Layer of count markers
feature_group = FeatureGroup(name='Provider Count (#)')

for each in final_state.iterrows():
    feature_group.add_child(Marker(location=[each[1]['latitude'], each[1]['longitude']], 
                  popup=("<b>" + each[1]['name'] + "</b>: " + locale.format_string("%d", each[1]['provider_count'], grouping=True)), 
                  icon=folium.Icon(icon_size = (1,1), color = 'beige'),
                 show = False))
m.add_child(feature_group)

## Gender Layer

p_gen_dict = dict(zip(final_state['state'].values, pd.get_dummies(final_state['nppes_provider_gender'])['M']))
step = cm.StepColormap(
    ['pink', 'lightblue'],
    vmin=0, vmax=1,
    index=[0,0.5,1],
    caption='male'
)

folium.GeoJson(
    us_states,
    name='Provider Gender Majority',
    style_function=lambda feature: {
        'fillColor': step(p_gen_dict[feature['id']]),
        'color': 'black',
        'weight': 1,
        'fillOpacity': 0.9,},
    show = False

## Specialty Layer
specialty_dict = final_state.set_index('state')['specialty_description']
def my_color_function(feature):
    if specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'Dentist':
        return '#33FF44'
    elif specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'Family Practice':
        return '#33FFAA'
    elif specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'General Practice':
        return '#33EEFF'
    elif specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'Internal Medicine':
        return '#3388FF'
    elif specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'Nurse Practitioner':
        return '#4433FF'
    elif specialty_dict[feature['id']] == 'Physician Assistant':
        return '#AA33FF'
    else:
        return 'gray'

folium.GeoJson(
    us_states,
    name='Provider Specialty Majority',
    style_function=lambda feature: {
        'fillColor': my_color_function(feature),
        'color': 'black',
        'weight': 1,
        'fillOpacity': 0.9,},
    show = False
).add_to(m)

Analysis of Demographic of Providers (State Level)¶

In [124]:

Above is an interactive map which geographically visualizes the distribution in demographic traits of Medicare Part D providers in the United States. These providers prescribe drugs for Medicare beneficiaries. Most of the providers are concentrated in California. The 5 states with the most providers are also the most populated states in the United States (Source: https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/us-states-by-population.html): California, New York, Texas, Florida, and Pennsylvania. These providers are predominantly male (3:2 ratio) and this trend is found across the country with only one state having predominantly female providers, which is Massachusetts. Most of the providers affiliated with Medicare are Nurse Practicioners followed by Family Practice. Surprisingly, a good amount of elderly folks also get their medication from dentists being the 3rd most popular specialty among the providers.

However, it is more interesting to see where there is a lack of providers, in which I will use beneficiary count per provider as the metric. The state with the highest beneficiary to provider ratio is in Puerto Rico. Unfortunately, this is not showing on the map since the geojson map of the United States does not include Puerto Rico as a state. On the mainland of the United States, the southern states have the highest beneficiary to provider ratio, with the top state being Alabama in which each provider has 194 beneficiaries on average. Surprisingly Florida has a lack of providers even though it is one of the states with the highest number of providers.

Having a lack of providers may mean that it is more difficult for beneficiaries in these states to get the medication that they need. These states would be a great market to look into for the medication delivery service.

This analysis of the demographics of the beneficiaries provides insight for the consumers the product will target. Medicare is a program for people who are 65 or older, certain younger people with disabilities, and people with End-Stage Renal Disease. Therefore, most beneficiaries are between the ages of 65 and 74. The states with highest average age of beneficiaries are in Hawaii, New Jersey, California, North Dakota, and South Dakota with the average being 71 years old.

In regards to the demographics of the beneficiaries, most are females (3:2 ratio). Southern states tend to have a slightly more imbalanced ratio, favoring females. As for the racial background, the beneficiaries are predominantly white except for Hawaii and Puerto Rico. The state with the most diversity is California, followed by New Mexico.

Therefore, the design of the app must be simple to use and gender-neutral. Since most of the beneficiaries are white, the language on the app can be kept as solely English.

Unlike Medicare, Medicaid helps with medical costs for some people with limited income and resources. Beneficiaries can be enrolled in only Medicare and both depending on their income level. Most beneficiaries are only enrolled in Medicare meaning that they above the income threshold. However, a good portion of beneficiaries residing in Alaska, District of Columbia, Maine, Mississippi, and New Mexico are enrolled in both. This signfies the disparity in income level among the states. This information can determine the price of the product. Given that most beneficiaries are above the income threshold, they may be open to pay high prices for the convenience of the delivery service.

CMS assigns risk scores per beneficiary which estimates how beneficiaries’ fee-for-service spending will compare to the overall average for the entire Medicare population. The average risk score is set at 1.08; beneficiaries with scores greater than that are expected to have above-average spending. (Source: https://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/Medicare-Provider-Charge-Data/Downloads/Prescriber_Methods.pdf) All the states have average scores greater than 1.08, meaning all states are expected to have above-average spending, which may be problematic since the government is underestimating the costs of Medicare. States with the highest risks are District of Columbia, Florida, Ohio, and Puerto Rico.

The analysis regarding Medicare metrics provides insights in the need for medication regulation in the Medicare Part D Program.

On average, each beneficiary submits 9 Medicare Part D claims for prescription and refills per year. However, the amount of claims submitted in Puerto Rico (13) and Arkansas (12) are way above 2 standard deviations from the average. Medication that have a 30 day supply tend to be refilled more often than necessary (12 times per year). The average for the country is 14 times while Puerto Rico receives 17 refills per year. This signifies that people may be abusing Medicare and getting more medication than they need. Day's supply is the number of days medication is to be taken. On average, beneficiaries receive a 395 day supply of medication. However, again Puerto Rican beneficiaries receive 466 day supply, on average. In fact, 27 states receive more than 395 days worth of supply per year.

The total drug cost includes the ingredient cost of the medication, dispensing fees, sales tax, and any applicable administration fees and is based on the amount paid by the Part D plan, Medicare beneficiary, government subsidies, and any other third-party payers. The average drug cost per beneficiary is \$921.80, but District of Columbia has the highest average drug cost which is 3.69 standard deviations above the mean, with an average of \\$1286.51. It would be interesting to see why the cost of drugs are so high in District of Columbia, and if the low social economic levels of the area contribute to this. In general, the New England states have an average drug cost per beneficiary above the national average. These states include New Jersey, New York, Maryland, and Massachusetts. The reason for this phenomenon may be found by looking more into the similarities between these states to see what contributes to such high drug costs per beneficiary.

Hypothesis Testing¶

From the analysis, I wanted to explore more on the significance in total drug costs per beneficiary in the New England states (New Jersey, New York, Maryland, and Massachusetts) being higher than the rest of the states. I am testing this hypothesis at the 5% significance level.

$H_0$: There is no difference in average total drug costs among the New England states and the rest of the states.

$H_A$: The average total drug costs among the New England states is higher than the rest of the states.

In [379]:
drug_cost_ne = us_provider[us_provider['nppes_provider_state'].isin(['NJ', 'NY', 'MD', 'MA'])][['nppes_provider_state', 'total_drug_cost', 'bene_count']]
drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost_p_b'] = drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost'] / drug_cost_ne['bene_count']
drug_cost_other = us_provider[np.logical_not(us_provider['nppes_provider_state'].isin(['NJ', 'NY', 'MD', 'MA']))][['nppes_provider_state', 'total_drug_cost', 'bene_count']]
drug_cost_other['total_drug_cost_p_b'] = drug_cost_other['total_drug_cost'] / drug_cost_other['bene_count']
In [402]:
# Sample Dataframe to have balanced dataset
drug_cost_other_sample = drug_cost_other.sample(len(drug_cost_ne))
In [403]:
mean_ne = np.mean(drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost_p_b'])
mean_other = np.mean(drug_cost_other_sample['total_drug_cost_p_b'])
print("Average Total Drug Cost for New England States: "+ str(round(mean_ne,2)))
print("Average Total Drug Cost for Other States: "+ str(round(mean_other,2)))
diff = np.abs(mean_ne - mean_other)
print(f'The difference between the New England states and other states drug cost per beneficiary is {diff}')

Average Total Drug Cost for New England States: 902.65
Average Total Drug Cost for Other States: 748.26
The difference between the New England states and other states drug cost per beneficiary is 154.38803866783644
In [404]:
# Bootstrap Permutation
bootstrap_replicates = np.empty(10000)
for i in range(10000):
    perm = np.random.permutation(np.concatenate((drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost_p_b'], drug_cost_other_sample['total_drug_cost_p_b'])))
    perm_ne = perm[:len(drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost_p_b'])]
    perm_other = perm[len(drug_cost_ne['total_drug_cost_p_b']):]
    bootstrap_replicates[i] = np.abs(np.mean(perm_ne) - np.mean(perm_other))
    
perm_pval = (np.sum(bootstrap_replicates >= diff)/10000)
print(f'p-value: {perm_pval}')

p-value: 0.0

With a p-value of 0, I am able to reject the null hypothesis! Therefore, there is significance in the average drug cost per beneficiary in the New England being higher than the rest of the states.

Conclusion¶

Given the demographics of the providers and the beneficiaries, there may be an opportunity of creating an online service of sending out prescription drugs to the elderly population. Most are most likely in nursing homes implied by most of the providers being Nurse Practicioners. However, elderly who cannot get their prescription as easily would benefit from this online service. The states to look into are the states lacking providers to support the number of beneficiaries, which are Alabama, Florida, Mississippi, Arkansas, and South Carolina. The design of the product should reflect the demographics of the beneficiaries which are between the ages of 65-74 and mainly females. The cost of the product should reflect the fact that most beneficiaries are above the income threshold to qualify for Medicaid. This threshold varies per state.

There can be a push for this product from the government level since there seems to be an issue of regulating drug use. The total drug cost in certain states are more than 3 standard deviations than the national average. Prescriptions tend to give out more than enough medication to beneficiaries. They receive more than 395 day supply per year, and refill medication with a 30 day supply more than 14 times per year. This may be evidence to support this push to have online prescription and mailing service.
